Wash and dry produce.

Thinly slice @jalapeño{1} into rounds, removing ribs and seeds for less heat. If you
like your chili a bit spicy, mince a few slices until you have @?minced jalapeño{1%tbsp}.
Remove @Italian pork sausage{9} from casing; discard casing.

> TIP: Use kitchen shears or a sharp knife to cut a slit in the casing lengthwise;
> it's a quick way to decase the sausage!

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add
sausage, @garlic powder{1}, and minced jalapeño if desired; cook, breaking up
meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

While sausage cooks, quarter @lime{1}. Drain @corn kernels{13.4%oz can}.

Add corn and @blackening spice{1} to pot with sausage; cook, stirring often,
until corn is lightly browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a small microwave-safe #bowl{}, combine sliced jalapeño, juice
from half the lime, and @sugar{3/4%tsp}. Microwave for ~{1%minute}. Set aside,
stirring occasionally, until ready to serve.

Stir @tomato paste{1.5%tbsp} into pot with sausage; cook, stirring, until coated,
~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @kidney beans{13.4%oz can} and their liquid, @chicken stock concentrate{2},
and @water{1/4%cup}. Bring to a boil over high heat. Cook, stirring occasionally,
until everything is warmed through, ~{30%seconds} more.

Turn off heat. Add a squeeze of lime juice to taste. Taste and season with @salt{1.5%tsp}
and @pepper{}.> TIP: If chili seems too thick, add a splash of water.

Divide chili between bowls; dollop with @sour cream{4} and top with as much pickled
jalapeño (draining first) as you like. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.